        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We choose the correlator setup to be able to observe all our lines at a resolution of ~ 0.16 km/s. For this reason, we are not making use of the averaging channels capability.

Our source does not possess any characteristic that require a high bandpass accuracy, therefore the bandpass accuracy achievable at band 6 is more than adequate for this project.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The data rate for this project is 18.5 MB/sec. As we need 0.16 km/s of spectral resolution, we are not averaging channels in the spectral setup. 
Such fine resolution is needed to resolve and fit properly the narrow spectral component of the CO line, which is ~ 1 km/s.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Although our source is extended, we are only interested in the inner region, ~ 6 asec. The angular resolution requested of 0.25 asec is adequate to study in detail the gas distribution in the central part of this AGB star. Our source does not have a complicated structure, making the imaging reliable in the observing mode we propose.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We take the spectrum information for 12CO 2-1 from Winters et al (2010). 
We are only interested in the central ~ 6" of the source.
Analysing the CO 2-1 spectrum (Winters et al (2007), we obtain a line peak value of 0.7 Jy/beam, with a beam of 1.67 X 0.94 arcsec. Assuming that the flux is distributed uniformly inside the beam, we obtain a flux of 0.11 Jy/beam, with an ALMA beam of 0.25 arcsec. Therefore, with the requested rms noise of 5 mJy/beam at 0.16 km/s resolution, we will detect the 12Co 2-1 line at 22 sigma. This s/n ratio is adequeate for modeling and fitting purposes.

Since we are also interested in detecting the plateau in the spectrum. From Winters et al data, we can see that the flux for that part of the spectrum is ~ 0.2 Jy/beam. Consequently, we will detect this feature at ~ 6 sigma, which is good enough to do our analysis. If needed, this part of the spectra can be rebinned in some channels, as the fwhm in this region is ~ 30 km/s.

The sensitivity calculation is based on the 12CO 2-1 line intensity. For the other molecules, we estimated the fluxes as there is no reported observations so far. 
The CO molecular species are own main target for this study, and the rest of the molecules are complementary. Therefore, the detection level for those lines will not affect the success of this project.

According to OT, an rms of 5 mJy/beam in a channel of 0.16 km/s, using a pwv of 1.26 mm (4th Octile), will require an integration time on source of ~ 35 min. Including calibration, the total time for this proposal is estimated in ~ 1.6 hr.

For continuum, we will have a minimum bandwidth of ~ 2GHz. This provides a sensitivity of ~ 40 microJy. Since the continuum level we expect from our source is ~ 16 mJy, we will be able to detect it at ~ 400 sigma.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
