    <prp:abstract>One of the key aspects that has not been fully understood in the stellar evolution is the mechanism that forms axisymmetric structures that are seen in proto-planetary (PPN) and planetary nebulae (PN), as well as the evolutionary phase at which occurs. In this project we focus in understanding the inner structure of the AGB star EP Aquarii, which presents a composite profile in CO and other molecular emission lines. Such profiles can have several formation mechanisms, with one of them being an equatorial disk or a rotating reservoir of material that in itself is one of the mechanisms proposed to explain the formation of the axisymmetric structures seen in PPN and PN. By studying the inner structure of EP Aqr we will be able to disentangle the mechanism that produces the composite profile and shed light into the formation of structure seen in later stages of stellar evolution.
</prp:abstract>
